## 2. Why These Two Frameworks Fit

The DOL framework answers a competency question: *what should workers know about AI?* Slow AI Kitchen answers an operating question: *how should workers use AI in governed professional work?* The two are not competing taxonomies. They are complementary layers. One defines the literacy floor; the other provides the production discipline that makes literacy operationally meaningful.

A worker who understands AI principles (DOL Content Area 1) but has never been required to define success criteria before prompting will still produce ungoverned output. A worker who follows the Kitchen's twelve steps but cannot explain why AI generates probabilistic outputs rather than deterministic answers will follow the method mechanically without understanding what it protects against. Both failures are real. Both are preventable when the frameworks operate together.

The structural alignment is not accidental. The DOL framework emphasizes human oversight, bounded AI use, output verification, accountability for outcomes and responsible deployment. Slow AI Kitchen was built on exactly these commitments before the DOL framework existed. The convergence reflects the fact that any serious approach to governed AI use arrives at the same set of controls. The difference is that the DOL framework expresses them as competencies to be learned, and Slow AI Kitchen expresses them as gates to be passed.

