## 4. Mapping: DOL Delivery Principles to Workshop Design

The DOL framework identifies seven delivery principles for effective AI literacy instruction. The Slow AI Kitchen workshop was designed independently but converges on the same pedagogical commitments. The following table maps each DOL delivery principle to the workshop elements that satisfy it.

| DOL Delivery Principle | Kitchen Workshop Element | Integration Note |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1. Enable Experiential Learning | Workshop Exercise (all modules) | The workshop requires teams to produce a genuine artifact on a real business problem, not a simulated one. Exercises run the full twelve-step sequence. The facilitator principle "reward clear framing, good constraints, quality of review" reinforces learning by doing. |
| 2. Embed Learning in Context | Workshop Exercise, Module 4 | Suitable exercise examples are drawn from the participants' own work: client advisories, policy summaries, workflow design, management briefings, risk analyses and training notes. Module 4 treats the tool used in the exercise as the subject of an organizational deployment question. |
| 3. Build Complementary Human Skills | Step 3 (Knife Work), Module 1 instruction | The manual first pass is the method's core mechanism for building and preserving the human skills that AI cannot replace. The method's teaching move — showing that the most dangerous AI outputs are often the most fluent — directly addresses critical thinking, judgment and domain expertise. |
| 4. Address Prerequisites to AI Literacy | See Integration Note | The core method assumes participants have baseline digital literacy and tool access. Organizations deploying this module in WIOA-funded or workforce board settings should add a pre-workshop readiness assessment covering device access, broadband connectivity and basic digital fluency. This is the one area where the DOL framework identifies a requirement that Slow AI Kitchen does not independently address, because the method was designed for professional knowledge workers rather than workforce entry populations. |
| 5. Create Pathways for Continued Learning | Step 9 post-action review, Step 12 operational audit cycle, Your Restaurant Pillar 5 | Step 9 turns the method into a learning system by requiring post-action review after every deployment decision. Step 12 requires updated training standards as tools evolve. Pillar 5 of Your Restaurant institutionalizes continuous improvement. The method's three-register architecture (Kitchen, Feast, Restaurant) is itself a progression pathway from individual discipline to organizational deployment to institutional program governance. |
| 6. Prepare Enabling Roles | Roles architecture (Steps 1–9 and Steps 10–12), Workshop Module 4 | The method defines both task roles (Preparer, Builder, Reviewer, Approver, Owner) and organizational roles (AI Owner, AI Operator, Executive Sponsor). Module 4 trains participants to assign brigade roles and training requirements. The facilitator principles provide a train-the-trainer framework. |
| 7. Design for Agility | Step 12 (Run the Event), Your Restaurant Pillars 4 and 5 | Step 12 requires periodic review of the tool registry against regulatory developments, new risk disclosures and operational experience. Pillar 4 manages the full AI lifecycle including version tracking and performance monitoring. Pillar 5 institutionalizes a regular review cycle for the governance framework itself. These elements satisfy the DOL's requirement for built-in adaptation mechanisms. |

