## 6. Facilitator Guidance for DOL-Aligned Delivery

Workshop facilitators deploying this module should make the following adjustments to the standard Slow AI Kitchen workshop.

### 6.1 Opening Frame

Add a brief reference to the DOL AI Literacy Framework in the opening session. Position Slow AI Kitchen as the operating method that delivers the competencies the DOL framework describes. The frame should be: the DOL tells us what workers need to know; the Kitchen teaches them how to do it under governed conditions. This takes no more than five minutes of the opening session and should not displace the core framing about discipline over access.

### 6.2 Module 1 Enhancement

When teaching Foundations (Steps 1 through 3), explicitly connect the manual first pass in Step 3 to DOL Content Area 3 (Direct AI Effectively). The DOL framework emphasizes that effective AI interaction depends on the user's ability to provide context and iterate strategically. The Kitchen's position is stronger: workers who have done the knife work arrive at Step 5 with the cognitive scaffolding to prompt well, not because they have been taught prompting tricks, but because they have already formed a judgment that the AI is being asked to extend. Make this point explicitly.

### 6.3 Module 2 Enhancement

When teaching Governance (Steps 4 through 6), connect Step 6 (Name the Chef de Partie) to DOL Content Area 5 (Use AI Responsibly). The DOL framework's language about maintaining accountability and avoiding treating AI responses as final or authoritative maps directly onto the Chef de Partie gate. Facilitators should surface this connection so that participants understand the Kitchen's accountability step is not a bureaucratic formality but a structural expression of the same responsible-use principle the federal government has identified as foundational.

### 6.4 Module 3 Enhancement

When teaching Execution (Steps 7 through 9), connect Step 8 (Taste Before Service) to DOL Content Area 4 (Evaluate AI Outputs). The DOL framework describes output evaluation as verifying factual accuracy, assessing completeness, spotting logical errors and aligning with strategic intent. The Kitchen's Step 8 operationalizes every one of these checks through the Definition of Done set in Step 2. Make the connection explicit: the DOL describes the competency; the Kitchen provides the mechanism.

### 6.5 Module 4 Enhancement

When teaching Organizational Deployment (Steps 10 through 12), connect the Feast's tool registry, brigade structure and operational audit to DOL Delivery Principles 5 (Create Pathways for Continued Learning), 6 (Prepare Enabling Roles) and 7 (Design for Agility). The DOL's language about structured routes to advanced skills, equipping managers and counselors, and built-in adaptation mechanisms maps directly onto the Feast architecture. Module 4 is where the organizational-scale alignment is most visible and most valuable for compliance documentation.

### 6.6 Workshop Outputs Addition

Add a twelfth workshop output to the standard eleven: a DOL AI Literacy Framework alignment summary. This is a one-page document produced by each team at the conclusion of the workshop, mapping their completed exercise artifacts to the five DOL content areas. It serves as both a learning exercise and a compliance record. For organizations in workforce development contexts, this document can be included in program reporting.

