## 9. Further Resources

The NIST Trustworthy and Responsible AI Resource Center at https://airc.nist.gov is the authoritative starting point for organizations that want to move beyond literacy alignment into structured AI risk management. The center hosts the AI Risk Management Framework (AI RMF 1.0), the AI RMF Playbook and a clause-level crosswalk mapping the AI RMF to ISO/IEC 42001. All three resources are free and maintained by the National Institute of Standards and Technology. Organizations operating in workforce development contexts will find the AI RMF's four functions — Govern, Map, Measure and Manage — directly aligned with the governance architecture described in the Slow AI Kitchen addendum, Your Restaurant.

Organizations that move from workforce literacy alignment into permanent AI program governance will find the complete reference architecture — covering NIST publications organized by governance pillar, primary regulatory instruments including the EU AI Act and Korea's AI Basic Act, OECD AI Principles, and the ISO/IEC standards catalogue anchored by 42001 — at the Slow AI Kitchen GitHub repository: [Restaurant Resources](https://github.com/rolldabones/slow-ai-kitchen/blob/main/restaurant%20resources). That resource file is organized by the same five-pillar structure (Governance, Risk Management, Regulatory Compliance, AI Lifecycle Management and Continuous Improvement) used throughout the Slow AI Kitchen system. It is a pathway for organizations ready to build the institutional layer, not a prerequisite for the Bridge documented here.

